Solar PV power yield depends on PV power generation potential (PVPOT) and installed capacity. PVPOT is a dimensionless value, which describes the performance of PV cells relative to the nominal power capacity under actual environmental conditions. Therefore, PVPOT multiplied by the nominal installed watts of PV power capacity is the actual PV power generation. Following previous studies15,43,62, we used daily T, I and W to calculate PVPOT:4PVPOT=PRIISTC\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{{{PV}}_{{POT}}}}\,=\,{P}_{{\mathrm{R}}}\frac{I}{{I}_{{{\mathrm{STC}}}}}$$\end{document}where I represents surface downwelling shortwave radiation and ISTC represents shortwave flux on the PV panel under standard test conditions, defined as a constant of 1,000âW mâ2. PR is the performance ratio, representing temperature influence on PV efficiency:5PR=1+Î³TcellâTSTC\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${P}_{{\mathrm{R}}}\,=1+\gamma \left({T}_{{{\mathrm{cell}}}}-{T}_{{{\mathrm{STC}}}}\right)$$\end{document}where Î³ is defined as â0.005âÂ°Câ1 in monocrystalline silicon solar panels, representing the negative impact on conversion efficiency, and TSTC is the cell temperature under standard test conditions (25âÂ°C). Tcell is the actual cell temperature, which is approximated by T, I and W:6Tcell=a1+a2ÃT+a3ÃI+a4ÃW\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${T}_{{{\mathrm{cell}}}}\,=a1+a2\times T+a3\times I+a4\times W$$\end{document}where a1, a2, a3 and a4 are taken as 4.3âÂ°C, 0.943 (unitless), 0.028âÂ°C (W mâ2)â1 and â1.528âÂ°C (m sâ1)â1, respectively. These coefficients represent the influence of meteorological conditions on the cell temperature. The ambient T determines the base temperature of the cell, a strong I increases the cell temperature and W decreases cell temperature. These coefficients are found to be fairly independent on site location and cell technology type63, which have been widely used to predict PV cell temperature15,43,64.

